title: 128 Manhattan Avenue
description: With renovations just completed, this bright historic townhouse with vast indoor and outdoor space awaits your arrival! Now, with an enormous price reduction! Located on what is arguably the prettiest block in Manhattan, this contemporary take on a classic pre-war home is now available to rent! Upon entering the parlor, you will be awed by the preponderance of light and the clean lines that define this home. High ceilings, a sleek working fireplace, and the oversized west-facing windows create a large and inviting entertaining space. Adjacent to the living area, through stately sliding doors, you will find a sizable dining room, overlooking the verdant backyard, and able to accommodate a large gathering. Also with a working fireplace, this room is framed by plentiful and artistic functional storage. Right off the dining area you will find a butlers pantry with a sink, lots of preparation space and cabinets, as well as a half bath. Head down to the garden floor, and you will find a spacious kitchen with a large adjacent space: perfect for dining, watching movies or tv, or just gathering. There is a new work island and new stainless-steel appliances. There is also a Murphy Bed and a gorgeous new full bath, perfect for any guest seeking the privacy of their own floor. In good weather, the large adjacent flagstone patio is ideal for al fresco dining or socializing. There is also a laundry room conveniently located en route to the patio. On the third floor, youll find two large bedrooms. Both have the restored original shutters (also found on the parlor floor and in all the other bedrooms) as well as a fireplace. The bath is newly renovated with Italian Marble and has double sinks as well as an additional washing machine. This bedroom connects to another, also with bathroom access, with east-facing windows overlooking the trees. There is also a terrace outside this second bedroom providing the perfect perch for your morning coffee. The top floor offers two more spacious bedrooms and a large bathroom in between. The newly renovated bath has a corner Jacuzzi and a skylight. A staircase to the roof provides ready access to additional unfinished space. Stately townhouses grace both sides of this tree-lined block, making it one of the most picturesque stretches in all New York City. Central Park, Morningside Park, two community gardens, Whole Foods, as well as bespoke restaurants and transportation are all right there. Become the next resident of this magnificent, meticulously maintained townhouse. Take advantage of the enviable patio for Summer Fun right off Central Park West! Now with a HUGE price reduction! (*Please note: 24-hour notice for showings appreciated.)

title: 110 Convent Avenue, 7
description: Beyond Central Park, across 110th Street and up to 155th, Upper Manhattan is encompassed by Harlem. Times change, and people come and go, but Harlem remains through it all. Once the site of George Washington‚Äôs first victory as U.S. Commander-in-Chief, the area‚Äôs status as a real New York City neighborhood began following the Civil War. Rowhouses were constructed starting in 1876 ‚Äî replacing freestanding homes ‚Äî to sustain population growth spurred on by public transportation‚Äôs arrival. The community expanded exponentially, however, necessitating massive apartment buildings to accommodate. Harlem perhaps has the perception of being a concrete urban jungle, but it is home to Marcus Garvey and Jackie Robinson parks and near several more ‚Äî including the North Woods/Harlem Meer portions of upper Central Park. Those green spaces add a touch of nature to this famed metropolitan neighborhood, done up in eclectic architectural styles and still beckoning to people from all over.

title: 67 6 W 10th Street, 7
description: When you want New York City without the city, you head to Greenwich Village. It is an area about as storybook as Manhattan gets, sporting leafy trees, distinctive buildings, and some uncharacteristic streets. Although gorgeous parks are far from unheard of across all five boroughs, Washington Square Park ‚Äî with its famous fountain and marble arch ‚Äî does stand in a class by itself. This iconic destination is a popular meeting place and area for cultural activities, making it a centerpiece the rest of the neighborhood sits around. There‚Äôs simply an energy to the park that radiates and shines throughout Greenwich Village. The area‚Äôs oldest remaining house is the c. 1799 Isaacs-Hendricks House, which has received some alterations and expansions over time. However, it‚Äôs the series of c. 1830s Greek Revival row houses north of Washington Square ‚Äî boasting stoops and brick facades ‚Äî that set the Village‚Äôs style in brownstone.
